      Oh Elon
   =20
 =20

Disclosure! A=C2=A0long time ago I used to work as a very junior mergers-an=
d-acquisitions lawyer at=C2=A0Wachtell, Lipton, Rosen & Katz. The hours wer=
e way too long, but I remain fond of the firm and the people there.=C2=A0Me=
anwhile I have no real personal connection to Elon Musk except that (1) he =
keeps doing weird stuff financial stuff for me to write about, which I love=
=C2=A0and (2) he keeps doing it while I am on vacation, which I do not love=
. And so I went away on Friday and Musk   did a thing.=C2=A0He sued Wachtel=
l, which represented Twitter Inc. when Musk=20
tried to get out of his deal to buy Twitter, claiming that Wachtell=E2=80=
=99s fee for that litigation =E2=80=94=C2=A0$90 million =E2=80=94=C2=A0was =
too big. I just want to be clear up front about my biases.=C2=A0
Wachtell is a fairly small law firm that makes a specialty of sell-side pub=
lic-company M&A work.=C2=A0It=C2=A0is =E2=80=9Camong the most profitable fi=
rms in the US.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Those facts are related. Sell-side public-comp=
any=C2=A0M&A work is a pretty lucrative legal specialty.
Partly this is for the usual obvious reasons: It is high-stakes, complicate=
d, high-pressure, high-dollar stuff. But there is another reason that is pe=
rhaps less obvious, which is that=C2=A0your clients don=E2=80=99t pay your =
bills. Here is how a public-company merger works:
=09A company decides to sell itself and hires lawyers.=09The buyer does a l=
ot of due diligence, looking into things like the company=E2=80=99s audited=
 financial statements, to figure out how much the target company is worth.=
=09A buyer signs an agreement to buy it for some fixed price, say $54.20 pe=
r share, in cash, to all of the target=E2=80=99s shareholders.
  [1]

=09After the agreement is signed, there is   a delay of several=C2=A0months=
 before it closes, during which the companies get regulatory approvals to m=
erge, the target=E2=80=99s shareholders vote on the deal, the buyer lines u=
p financing, etc.=09During that delay, the target continues operating as an=
 independent company, making its own business decisions with limited coordi=
nation with the buyer.=09The agreement  contains a covenant saying that the=
 target will operate =E2=80=9Cin the ordinary course of business=E2=80=9D a=
nd won=E2=80=99t make any drastic changes, pay out any huge bonuses, etc., =
so that, when the deal closes, the buyer gets more or less the same company=
 that it thought it was buying. But with a big public company, this covenan=
t can=E2=80=99t be all that fine-grained; the company just has to be able t=
o continue making business decisions. For one thing, its own expert executi=
ves need=C2=A0to make lots of decisions to preserve the target=E2=80=99s va=
lue for the buyer when the deal eventually closes.
  [2]
=C2=A0Also=C2=A0though the deal might=C2=A0not=C2=A0close: What if the shar=
eholders vote no, or the buyer doesn=E2=80=99t get its financing? Then the =
company will need to be ready to stay independent. The executives need to k=
eep running the company on behalf of its shareholders until the moment the =
check clears and the merger closes.=09Eventually the deal closes, the buyer=
 pays the cash, it becomes the owner of the target, and it can do whatever =
it wants. It can fire the executives, make the business decisions, etc.=09A=
t closing, the buyer pays the amount of cash that it agreed to pay in the m=
erger agreement. If it agreed to pay $54.20 at signing, it pays $54.20 at c=
losing, even if circumstances have changed over the intervening months. If =
the market fell, or the target company had a bad quarter, or if its expense=
s got a bit out of hand, the buyer still pays the same amount.=C2=A0=09You =
could imagine a different system: The buyer could get a price adjustment fo=
r changes in cash; it could agree to pay, like, =E2=80=9C$10 billion, but i=
f the target has less than $500 million of cash at closing, we will reduce =
the price by the difference.=E2=80=9D And this is not uncommon in private-c=
ompany M&A: If the seller of the target is a private equity firm, it can ag=
ree to a price adjustment. It is harder in public deals, though, mostly bec=
ause the target company=E2=80=99s public shareholders have to vote on the d=
eal, and you need to tell them the price so they can have an informed vote.=
 And so public deals don=E2=80=99t really have price adjustments for things=
 like how much cash is left in the target at closing.
  [3]

=09Instead, they just have that =E2=80=9Cordinary course=E2=80=9D covenant:=
 If the target spends=C2=A0much too much=C2=A0money between signing and clo=
sing, the buyer can=C2=A0walk away, say =E2=80=9Cyou didn=E2=80=99t operate=
 in the ordinary course like you promised, so I don=E2=80=99t have to close=
.=E2=80=9D Or it can=C2=A0threaten=C2=A0to walk away, and use that to reneg=
otiate the price.=C2=A0(There are other covenants and representations that =
have to be true at closing. A big one is the =E2=80=9Cmaterial adverse effe=
ct=E2=80=9D representation; if the company spends so much money that it cau=
ses a material adverse effect on its business, the buyer can walk away. But=
 that=E2=80=99s hard to do.)=C2=A0But if the target spends=C2=A0somewhat to=
o much=C2=A0money between signing and closing, there is not a lot the buyer=
 can do about it: It probably can=E2=80=99t walk away from the deal unless =
the spending is too egregious and out-of-the-ordinary-course, and it can=E2=
=80=99t just cut the price to make up for the target=E2=80=99s extra spendi=
ng.=09The result is that every dollar that the target company spends betwee=
n signing and closing is=C2=A0free, to the target=E2=80=99s shareholders.=
=C2=A0They get their $54.20 per share no matter what; the cash left in the =
company=E2=80=99s treasury is no longer their concern. Every dollar that th=
