<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A $90 million payment isn't unusual for such a=
 consequential case, said law-firm consultant Kent Zimmermann from Zeughaus=
er Group. "I'd be surprised if=C2=A0Wachtell=C2=A0was faulted for the amoun=
t they charged, considering the stakes and the outcome," he said.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Wachtell=C2=A0is known to be a leading law fir=
m for cases like the Twitter one, he added. "There's a limited supply of fi=
rms like=C2=A0Wachtell=C2=A0and a lot of demand for them, which drives the =
price up," he said.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway though Musk=E2=80=99s complaint has lot=
s of fun details about how Wachtell=E2=80=99s billing works. It=E2=80=99s a=
 little casual:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Both the August 26 Hourly Invoice =
and the September 28 Hourly Invoice were approved for payment despite flagr=
antly improper billing practices. For example, six Wachtell timekeepers =E2=
=80=A6 billed a combined $2,200,893.75 in those two invoices with completel=
y blank time entry descriptions. One Wachtell associate billed approximatel=
y $935,000 across the two invoices, with all of her time entry descriptions=
 limited to either =E2=80=9Cstrategy=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cfactual analysis=
=E2=80=9D without further elaboration.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Though all of this is much more detailed than =
the final bill, which is just =E2=80=9Cfor all legal services relating to t=
he acquisition of Twitter by Elon Musk through the closing: $90,000,000.00.=
=E2=80=9D<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-6" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-col=
or: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The final bill was based not on hours devoted =
to strategy or otherwise, but on deal size: Wachtell sent Twitter a memo<a =
class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-7" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transpar=
ent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[7]</span>
</a> justifying its $90 million fee, which says that =E2=80=9Cas we discuss=
ed, in engagements relating to pending transactions as to which a premium f=
ee is contemplated, our Firm often receives a fee in the range of 60 to 80 =
percent of the fees paid to investment advisors.=E2=80=9D That=E2=80=99s pr=
etty good! If you are the law firm getting paid 60% to 80% of the fees paid=
 to the investment banks on a deal, you are doing=C2=A0<em>better=C2=A0</em=
>than the banks:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Many big deals have multiple banks, so=
 each bank is probably getting something like 50% or less of the total bank=
ing fees. If the law firm is getting 60%, that=E2=80=99s more.<a class=3D"f=
ootnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-8" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !impor=
tant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[8]</span>
</a>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Banks are largely in the business=
 of=C2=A0<em>marketing=C2=A0</em>mergers, and a banker will spend a lot of =
time doing unpaid work pitching deals to companies for every one deal she c=
ompletes and gets paid for. Lawyers are much more likely to work on actual =
deals and get paid for them.=C2=A0</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is also this on the=C2=A0<em>timing=C2=
=A0</em>of that payment:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Immediately following the Twitter =
board=E2=80=99s rubber-stamp approval, [Twitter Chief Legal Officer Vijaya]=
 Gadde signed Wachtell=E2=80=99s letter agreement. Then, to ensure that the=
 eleventh-hour fee payment went through before the Musk Parties (Twitter=E2=
=80=99s new owners) could learn about the massive gift included in that fee=
, [Twitter General Counsel Sean] Edgett expedited the wire payment on the i=
nvoice for the balance ($84,294,962.97) of the $90 million total fee that W=
achtell had submitted to Twitter the day before. Twitter=E2=80=99s $84 mill=
ion wire to Wachtell was posted only ten minutes before Gadde and=C2=A0Edge=
tt were terminated upon the closing of the merger.=C2=A0</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yes! Right! Ten minutes is the normal amount o=
f time. If you pay Wachtell a $90 million success fee <em>30=C2=A0</em>minu=
tes before closing, you haven=E2=80=99t had your success yet: What if somet=
hing goes wrong in those 30 minutes, the deal doesn=E2=80=99t close, and Wa=
chtell keeps the money? If you pay Wachtell a $90 million success fee 10 mi=
nutes=C2=A0<em>after=C2=A0</em>closing, you might not pay: =E2=80=9CYou=E2=
=80=9D 10 minutes before closing are the company who hired Wachtell as your=
 trusted adviser to sell yourself; =E2=80=9Cyou=E2=80=9D 10 minutes after c=
losing are the guy who=C2=A0<em>bought=C2=A0</em>the company after negotiat=
ing <em>against</em> Wachtell. The right time to pay Wachtell=E2=80=99s gia=
nt bill is minutes, perhaps seconds, before closing.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now, Musk=C2=A0<em>did=C2=A0</em>tell Twitter =
not to do this. He complains that Twitter paid the fee even though he told =
them not to:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Musk Parties moved up the sche=
duled closing of the Merger Transaction by one day to October 27, 2022. At =
5:11 a.m.=C2=A0(8:11 a.m. Eastern) on the morning of October 27, counsel fo=
r the Musk Parties sent a directive on behalf of their client instructing T=
witter, Inc. =E2=80=9Cto immediately discontinue all outbound payments and =
other disbursements to third parties in order to assist Mr. Musk=E2=80=99s =
funds flow preparations for the completion of the pending merger.=E2=80=9D =
See Exhibit 16 (the =E2=80=9CClosing Day Directive=E2=80=9D). The Closing D=
ay Directive also provided advance instructions =E2=80=9Cin anticipation of=
 the imminent completion of the merger=E2=80=9D with respect to =E2=80=9Cou=
tbound payments and disbursements to third parties following completion of =
the merger,=E2=80=9D explicitly including =E2=80=9Coutside advisors, includ=
ing, without limitation, financial advisors, legal advisors, accounting adv=
isors, litigation experts, and all other external advisors.=E2=80=9D The Cl=
osing Day Directive was an unequivocal statement on behalf of Twitter=E2=80=
=99s residual claimants of the corporation=E2=80=99s preference to pause ou=
tbound payments pending that day=E2=80=99s closing so that the company=E2=
=80=99s new owner could have =E2=80=9Ca reasonable opportunity to review su=
ch payments.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Well! He sent Twitter a letter<a class=3D"foot=
note-index" href=3D"#footnote-9" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !importan=
t; display: inline-block;">
<span>[9]</span>
</a>:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">
<em>Asking=C2=A0</em>Twitter not to pay any bills before closing, and</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">
<em>Instructing=C2=A0</em>Twitter not to pay any bills after closing.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One second after closing, Musk owned Twitter, =
and could tell Twitter not to pay any bills. (And he did, and he has gotten=
 sued for it.) But one second before closing, Musk did=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</=
em>own Twitter, and Twitter could pay all the bills it wanted to. He asked =
it not to, and it did anyway, and that was fine. =E2=80=9CTwitter executive=
s ignored the first half of the Closing Day Directive and instead accelerat=
ed Twitter=E2=80=99s outbound payments to third parties,=E2=80=9D complains=
 Musk.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">By the way, it is not totally clear to me whet=
her Musk knew the size of Wachtell=E2=80=99s bill before closing. The compl=
aint says this:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Around this time, the Musk Parties=
 requested details from Twitter regarding its expected transaction expenses=
, including legal fees. On October 11, 2022, Twitter emailed Wachtell to re=
quest an estimate of Wachtell=E2=80=99s October fees =E2=80=9Cassuming a cl=
osing date of 10/28/22.=E2=80=9D Wachtell does not appear to have ever sent=
 that estimate or any details regarding its hourly billing or expenses=E2=
=80=94let alone an invoice or its hourly fees and expenses=E2=80=94in conne=
ction with its work on the merger litigation after August 31, 2022.=C2=A0</=
p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But it also says that on Oct. 14, =E2=80=9CTwi=
tter circulated a draft chart of transaction expenses to its counsel and li=
sted $95 million for Wachtell=E2=80=99s fees,=E2=80=9D and that on Oct. 24,=
 they agreed on $90 million and Twitter said =E2=80=9Cwe can update our tra=
nsaction expenses file.=E2=80=9D My assumption is that Twitter=C2=A0<em>did=
=C2=A0</em>send Musk a list of transaction expenses before closing, and Mus=
k didn=E2=80=99t focus on it until afterwards, but I am not really sure.</p=
>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In any case, what I do know is that (1) Musk=
=C2=A0<em>asked=C2=A0</em>for the list of transaction expenses before closi=
ng and (2) he =E2=80=9Cmoved up the scheduled closing of the Merger,=E2=80=
=9D so he must have either gotten what he asked for or decided he didn=E2=
=80=99t care. You could imagine Musk demanding a list of transaction expens=
es, not closing the deal until he got it, getting it, reviewing it, saying =
=E2=80=9Cthis Wachtell bill is too big,=E2=80=9D and refusing to close the =
deal until it was renegotiated. Or you could imagine him settling the merge=
r litigation by signing some sort of settlement agreement that covered, amo=
ng other things, litigation expenses. But he didn=E2=80=99t do that. He set=
tled the merger litigation by saying =E2=80=9Cnever mind, I=E2=80=99ll clos=
e the deal,=E2=80=9D not a negotiated settlement but a pure capitulation. A=
nd then, once he did that, he closed the deal as quickly as possible. He di=
d everything impetuously, and one result of that is that he paid a $90 mill=
ion fee to the law firm that beat him. And now he is complaining! Fine. But=
 it is only his fault.</p>
